The memo authorized Bush to use military force preemptively against terrorist groups post-9/11.
It argued for the president's authority to combat terrorism, even if not directly linked to the attacks.
Gonzales faced criticism for his role in advising Bush on interrogation methods.
The administration defended its stance on torture, citing national security concerns.
Yoo, a key figure in drafting the memo, justified the legal reasoning behind it.
The controversy surrounding the memo highlighted the administration's approach to counterterrorism and interrogation practices.
The Senate debated the definition of torture, questioning the administration's tactics and accountability.
